ttribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Chong, Young, Chun, Hang, Ho, In, Jung, Maeng, Mijin, Rong, Hyong, Pong, Then, Yom, Lanh, Nu.  Cambodian Chea, Chhay, Chheng, Chhom, Voeun, Yoeun.  Spanish Alejandro, Angel, Miguel, Ricardo, Secundino, Tomas.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 阮, see   Ruan   3.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surnames 殷 and 尹, see   Yin   1 and 2."],"variants":[{"name":"Ruan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Ping, Xiu, Ying, Biao, Chao, Cheng, Guang, Guohua, Hua, Huiming, Jia, Jian Hua.  Spanish Jorge, Arnulfo, Arturo, Blanca, Carlos, Eduardo, Gregorio, Guillermo, Javier, Jesus, Jose, Josefina.","Irish and Scottish: variant of   Ruane  .","Spanish (<b>Ruán</b>): nickname from <i>ruán</i> ‘roan’ (a color of horses), a variant of   Ruano  ."]}]},{"name":"Blanco","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Juan, Carlos, Jorge, Luis, Raul, Francisco, Miguel, Julio, Pedro, Jesus.","Spanish: nickname for a man with white or fair hair or a pale complexion, from <i>blanco</i> ‘white’.","Italian (Sicily): variant of   Bianco  , perhaps influenced by French <i>blanc</i> or Spanish <i>blanco</i> (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Bianco","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Vito, Angelo, Salvatore, Carmine, Antonio, Rocco, Aniello, Francesco, Luca, Luigi, Pasquale, Sal.","Italian: from <i>bianco</i> ‘white’ (of ancient Germanic origin; compare Old High German <i>blanc</i> ‘bright, shining, white, beautiful’), originally applied as a nickname for a man with white or fair hair or a pale complexion, or for someone who habitually wore white, especially in jousting or other competitions, and later used as a personal name. Compare   Lo Bianco  ."]},{"name":"Blanca","meanings":["Spanish: from the feminine form of   Blanco   ‘white’."]}]},{"name":"Dama","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Mainly North American: of unknown origin, perhaps a transferred use of a surname that is fairly common in the United States. This may be of Irish origin, although the surname is not known in Ireland. <i>Dana</i> or <i>Ana</i> was the name of an ancient Irish fertility goddess, and this was also used in medieval times as a girl's name, However, it is not clear whether there is any connection between this name and the modern given name, which is sometimes also used as a feminine form of   Dan   or   Daniel .  Modern use as a boy's given name began in honour of  Richard Henry Dana  (  1815–82 ), author of Two Years before the Mast, who supported the rights of fugitive slaves before and during the Civil War. The popularity of the given name was increased by the fame of the film star  Dana Andrews  (  1909–92 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Dama En Blanco was born about 1134, in England. She had at least 2 sons with Lord William Wandesley of Selston. She died in 1177, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 44."},"et":{"about 1134–1177":"umbes 1134–1177","1134–1176":"1134–1176","1154–1220":"1154–1220","1157–1231":"1157–1231","1134–1177":"1134–1177","1157":"1157","1134":"1134","1177":"1177","1176":"1176","1231":"1231","1220":"1220","1154":"1154","about 1134":"umbes 1134","about 1157":"umbes 1157","about 1154":"umbes 1154","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England","England":"England","East Retford, Nottinghamshire, England":"East Retford, Nottinghamshire, England","Selston, Nottinghamshire, England":"Selston, Nottinghamshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1134–1177":"noin 1134–1177","1134–1176":"1134–1176","1154–1220":"1154–1220","1157–1231":"1157–1231","1134–1177":"1134–1177","1157":"1157","1134":"1134","1177":"1177","1176":"1176","12